    {
      "num": 13,
      "text": "In the context of fraud risk management, what is the primary weakness of relying solely on detective controls without preventive controls?",
      "tag": "Internal Controls & Risk Mitigation",
      "options": [
        "B. Detective controls are more expensive and require specialized technology",
        "A. Detective controls only identify fraud after loss has occurred; preventive controls stop fraud before it happens",
        "D. Detective controls fail to provide management with real-time transaction monitoring",
        "C. Detective controls cannot generate audit evidence admissible in legal proceedings"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Detective controls address fraud post-occurrence, minimizing prevention value. Per COSO and ACFE standards, a balanced framework combines preventive controls (barriers) and detective controls (monitoring). Prevention reduces financial and reputational harm.",
      "justification_wrong": "Cost, evidentiary issues, and real-time capability are secondary concerns. The fundamental weakness is timing: detectives identify damage already done; preventive controls avoid it.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "prevention_deterrence/quiz_005_en.json"
    },
