      "topic": "Fraud Risk Management",
      "subtopic": "Fraud Risk Assessment Methodologies",
      "question": "A large multinational corporation is implementing a fraud risk assessment process. The fraud examination team is evaluating which methodology to use for identifying and prioritizing fraud risks across various business units. Which of the following approaches would be MOST effective for conducting a comprehensive fraud risk assessment?",
      "options": [
        "A. Using historical fraud incident data exclusively to predict future fraud risks and focusing resources only on areas where fraud has previously occurred",
        "B. Conducting brainstorming sessions with cross-functional teams including finance, operations, legal, and internal audit to identify potential fraud schemes, assessing both likelihood and impact, and mapping risks to specific business processes",
        "C. Implementing automated data analytics tools to monitor 100% of transactions without conducting qualitative risk assessments or stakeholder interviews",
        "D. Relying solely on external audit findings and regulatory examination reports to identify fraud risks without conducting internal fraud risk workshops"
