      "explanation": "Option B is correct because an effective fraud risk assessment requires a combination of qualitative methods (brainstorming sessions with diverse stakeholders who understand different aspects of the business) and structured analysis (assessing likelihood and impact, process mapping). This approach aligns with best practices in fraud risk management by: (1) leveraging diverse perspectives to identify risks that may not be apparent from data alone, (2) evaluating both the probability and potential magnitude of fraud risks, and (3) linking identified risks to specific processes for targeted control design. Option A is inadequate because it ignores emerging fraud risks and assumes past patterns will repeat. Option C over-relies on technology without the strategic framework that qualitative assessment provides. Option D is reactive and depends on external parties who may not understand internal fraud vulnerabilities as thoroughly as internal stakeholders.",
