      "topic": "Fraud Risk Management",
      "subtopic": "Fraud Risk Assessment Methodologies",
      "question": "A multinational manufacturing company is conducting its annual fraud risk assessment. The fraud risk management team has identified several potential fraud schemes across different business units. Which of the following approaches would be MOST effective in prioritizing these identified fraud risks for remediation?\n\nA. Rank all identified fraud risks solely based on their potential financial impact to the organization\n\nB. Evaluate each fraud risk using a combination of likelihood of occurrence and potential impact, considering both inherent and residual risk levels\n\nC. Prioritize fraud risks based exclusively on the number of times similar frauds have occurred in the industry\n\nD. Focus remediation efforts only on fraud risks that have materialized in the company's history",
      "options": {
        "A": "Rank all identified fraud risks solely based on their potential financial impact to the organization",
        "B": "Evaluate each fraud risk using a combination of likelihood of occurrence and potential impact, considering both inherent and residual risk levels",
        "C": "Prioritize fraud risks based exclusively on the number of times similar frauds have occurred in the industry",
        "D": "Focus remediation efforts only on fraud risks that have materialized in the company's history"
      },
      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "Option B is correct because effective fraud risk assessment requires a comprehensive approach that considers multiple dimensions. Evaluating both likelihood and impact provides a balanced view of risk severity. Additionally, considering inherent risk (risk before controls) versus residual risk (risk after controls) helps identify where existing controls may be insufficient and where resources should be allocated. This methodology allows for risk-based prioritization that is more sophisticated than single-factor analysis.\n\nOption A is incorrect because focusing solely on financial impact ignores the likelihood of occurrence. A high-impact but low-likelihood risk may receive unwarranted priority over a moderate-impact but high-likelihood risk that poses greater overall danger.\n\nOption C is incorrect because industry trends, while informative, may not reflect the specific risk environment of the company. Each organization has unique vulnerabilities based on its controls, culture, and business model.\n\nOption D is incorrect because it takes a reactive rather than proactive approach. Fraud risk management should identify and mitigate emerging risks before they materialize, not just address historical issues. This approach would leave the organization vulnerable to new fraud schemes.",
